title: For Sale:  1933 Izhevsk Mosin Nagant M91/30 with Hex Receiver
postcontent: I have inspected hundreds of M91/30s, and this is by far the nicest I've ever seen. This rifle is nicer than anything you will find at Cabela's or Gander Mountain. All parts are original and were manufactured in 1933 at the Izhevsk arsenal in Russia. All cosmoline has been thoroughly removed from all parts of the rifle, and the bolt has been polished to a beautiful shine. The hex receiver has a beautiful, smooth blue finish. Unlike the wartime rifles, this piece was milled with care and with much more attention to detail. All numbered parts match, and all non-numbered parts bear the Izzy markings. The wood has been treated with oil (typical of the earlier pre-war rifles) and not that yucky dark lacquer that you find on the vast majority of M91/30s. I will also throw in a lovely, sharp bayonet along with 40 rounds of Barnaul 7.62x54R. Price is $225 and is FIRM, cash only, no trades. Sorry, but any offers for trades or less than $225 cash will be ignored. If interested, please TEXT (214) 519-9102. Thanks for looking!!!

title: For Sale:  Rossi R92 Stainless with 20" Barrel
postcontent:
Have you ever gotten something that, once you got and shot it you realized it wasn't for you?  

I got this rifle not too long ago, lubed it, and shot it at the range.  I found out three things.  First, it cycles 38 a little better than .357 - maybe 1-3 .357 rounds out of 20 that didn't chamber easily in my experience, possibly attributable to short-stroking the action on my part.  Second, it's pretty accurate at 50 yards both with .357 (a little above point of aim) and .38 (a little below point of aim).  Third, I realized that I didn't like it very much.  

Part of my problem I guess is that redundant safety switch on the bolt; the whole time I've owned this I've not moved it more than about 5-6 times.  It's also ugly and has no place on a lever-action.  I thought I could get used to it but it just ruins the lines of the rifle for me.  Somebody else may either like it/accept it or be willing to put in the effort to get it removed/replaced.  

It's had about 50 rounds down the pipe, and has had multiple dummy rounds of both .38 and .357 cycled through the action (it seems to like real rounds better than the light-weight dummy rounds).  Like all lever-actions it doesn't seem to like being short-stroked - indeed, I'd say this one is pretty sensitive to short-stroking.  

Please contact me by email only.  Please also note that while I am obviously looking to sell it I'm not giving it away either; at the quoted price I'm taking a loss, so if I can't get that I'll be getting it cleaned and lubed and keeping it for a while.  Please keep these things in mind when making any offers.  I'm not interested in trades at this time.

As always, the arm is as is.  I will require an Ohio DL for ID purposes and a receipt to be signed.

Thanks.
